**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**
Feature

**What is the current behavior?**
`<Suspense children={() => {}} />` is not supported.

**What is the expected behavior?**
As mentioned [here](https://github.com/facebook/react/issues/13947#issuecomment-465743800) before, I hope that there will be support for `children` to be a render prop in `<Suspense />`. Why? I currently have the following case where I dislike to define another component only for loading async data
```javascript
function ShowModal({ itemId }) {
  return (
    <Modal open>
      <Suspense fallback={<p>Loading ...</p>}>
      {() => {
        const item = ItemStorage.read(itemId);

        return (
          <Modal.Header>
            <Modal.Title>{item.name}</Modal.Title>
          </Modal.Header>
          <Modal.Body>
          { /* ... stuff with data of item ... */ }
          </Modal.Body>
        );
      })
      </Suspense>
    </Modal>
  );
}
```
Currently this does not work because `children` is not allowed to be a function. So I have to define another component whos only task is to load the data and pass it to into the right place. I think there should be an easier solution, like the one used above. (To be honest, the code above works, **but** only because I use a wrapper component around the native React Suspense component.)

My currently wrapper component is defined like this:
```javascript
function SuspenseRenderChildren({ children }) {
  return children(); // really? :/
}

function Suspense({ children, ...props }) {
  if (typeof children === "function") {
    return (
      <React.Suspense {...props}>
        <SuspenseRenderChildren children={children} />
      </React.Suspense>
    );
  } else {
    return (
      <React.Suspense {...props} children={children} />
    );
  }
}
```
Therefore I create some kind of *wrapper hell* because in the worst case I render the following ...
```javascript
<Suspense>
  <React.Suspense>
    <SuspenseRenderChildren />
  </React.Suspense>
</Suspense>
```
... where it could be just ...
```javascript
<React.Suspense />
```

